import json
import os

base = "C:/Users/user/Documents/trust-agent-desktop/src/data/roles"

def expand_file(lang, extra_content):
    fn = os.path.join(base, f"{lang}-language-tutor.json")
    with open(fn, "r", encoding="utf-8") as f:
        d = json.load(f)
    old_len = len(d["systemPrompt"])
    d["systemPrompt"] = d["systemPrompt"] + extra_content
    with open(fn, "w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
        json.dump(d, f, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2)
    new_len = len(d["systemPrompt"])
    print(f"{lang}: {old_len} -> {new_len} chars {'OK' if new_len >= 10000 else 'NEEDS MORE'}")
    return new_len

# Catalan
expand_file("catalan", "\n\nCOMPLETE PHONOLOGICAL SYSTEM:\nCatalan has a rich vowel system with 7 stressed vowels: a /a/, e-open /e/, e-close /e/, i /i/, o-open /o/, o-close /o/, u /u/. In unstressed positions, these reduce to 3 (a and e-open merge to schwa, o-open and u merge). This vowel reduction is a key feature. Consonants include the palatal lateral /l/ (written ll), the palatal nasal /n/ (written ny), and geminate l (written l with a dot, punt volat). The voiced and voiceless sibilant pairs /s/-/z/ and /sh/-/zh/ are phonemic.\n\nCATALAN VS SPANISH:\nKey differences that learners must understand: Catalan has 8 vowel phonemes (stressed) vs Spanish 5. Catalan has vowel reduction (unstressed vowels change) while Spanish does not. Catalan uses articles el/la/els/les (not el/la/los/las). Catalan has two past tenses in regular use: periphrastic past (vaig cantar) and preterite (canti). Catalan pronouns have a weak/strong system similar to French. Word-final consonant clusters are common (camp, text, llarg) unlike Spanish.\n\nDIALECTAL VARIATION:\nTwo major dialect blocks: Eastern (Central, Balearic, Rossellonese/Northern) and Western (North-Western, Valencian). Central Catalan (Barcelona-based) is the standard. Valencian is often politically treated as a separate language but linguistically a Catalan dialect. Balearic has archaic features including the article es/sa (from Latin ipse). Key pronunciation differences: Eastern varieties reduce unstressed a/e to schwa, Western do not.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Not producing the schwa in unstressed positions - essential for natural Catalan.\n2. Confusing Catalan with Spanish patterns and vocabulary.\n3. Not mastering the two past tense system (periphrastic past is more common in speech).\n4. Failing to produce the palatal lateral ll and geminate l (punt volat).\n5. Not understanding the weak pronoun cliticization system (en, hi, el, la, etc.).\n6. Gender agreement errors with the Catalan article system.\n\nWEAK PRONOUN SYSTEM:\nCatalan has a complex system of weak (clitic) pronouns that attach to verbs: en (partitive/locative from), hi (locative/indirect), em/et/es/ens/us/es (reflexive/object). These combine and contract: me + el = mel, te + en = ten. This system is more complex than Spanish and resembles French/Italian.\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nCatalan is inseparable from Catalan national identity. The language was suppressed under Franco (1939-1975) and its revival is a source of pride. Understanding castells (human towers), Sant Jordi day (books and roses), Sardana dance, and Catalan cuisine (pa amb tomaquet, crema catalana) provides essential cultural grounding.\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nJunta Permanent de Catala certificates: levels A1-C2 (Basico through Superior). CIEFC (Certificat Internacional d'Estudis de Filologia Catalana). Required for certain professional positions in Catalonia.")

# Danish
expand_file("danish", "\n\nCOMPLETE PHONOLOGICAL SYSTEM:\nDanish is notorious for its pronunciation, which diverges dramatically from its spelling. The STOD (glottal stop/creaky voice) is a suprasegmental feature that distinguishes words: hun (she, with stod) vs hund (dog, without stod). Danish has approximately 27 vowel phonemes (one of the richest vowel systems of any language), including front rounded vowels: y (rounded i), oe (rounded e), aa (open back). The soft d (blaest d) is NOT a d but an approximant similar to English th in this - but even softer, almost an l-like sound. Many consonants weaken or disappear between vowels.\n\nDANISH SPELLING vs PRONUNCIATION:\nDanish spelling preserves historical pronunciations that have dramatically shifted in speech. The letter d between vowels becomes the soft d. Final -e is often silent. The combination -ig becomes like English -ee. The letter r is a uvular approximant that colors adjacent vowels. These sound changes make Danish one of the hardest Scandinavian languages to understand orally, even for Swedes and Norwegians.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Pronouncing d as English d in all positions instead of the soft d.\n2. Not producing the stod (glottal stop feature) - changes word meaning.\n3. Pronouncing all letters as written instead of applying the extensive reduction rules.\n4. Not mastering the front rounded vowels y and oe.\n5. Confusing common/neuter gender (en/et articles).\n6. Word order errors: Danish uses V2 (verb-second) word order in main clauses.\n\nDANISH VS NORWEGIAN VS SWEDISH:\nWritten Danish and Norwegian Bokmal are very similar (historically, Norway used Danish as its written language). Spoken Danish is much harder to understand due to pronunciation reduction. Key differences: Danish has stod where Swedish has pitch accent. Danish soft d has no equivalent in Swedish/Norwegian. Mutual intelligibility: Swedes and Norwegians understand each other well but often struggle with spoken Danish.\n\nGRAMMAR SYSTEM:\nTwo genders: common (en-words) and neuter (et-words). Definite article is suffixed: en hund (a dog) -> hunden (the dog), et hus (a house) -> huset (the house). Double definiteness with adjectives: den store hund (the big dog) - both article AND suffix. V2 word order: verb must be second element in main clauses. Two-part negation placement differs from English.\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nHygge (cozy togetherness) is central to Danish culture and appears in daily vocabulary. Janteloven (the Law of Jante - social conformity). Danish design and architecture vocabulary. Food: smoerrebroed (open sandwiches), frikadeller, flaesk. Understanding Danish understatement and directness in communication.\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nStudieproven (Study Test): required for university admission in Denmark. Prover i Dansk 1, 2, 3 (PD1, PD2, PD3): official Danish language tests at different levels. Danskproven (Danish Test): required for permanent residency.")

# Dutch
expand_file("dutch", "\n\nCOMPLETE PHONOLOGICAL SYSTEM:\nDutch consonants: p /p/, b /b/, t /t/, d /d/, k /k/, f /f/, v /v/, s /s/, z /z/, x /x/ (written ch or g, the famous Dutch guttural - varies from uvular fricative in the north to velar fricative in the south), h /h/, m /m/, n /n/, ng /ng/, l /l/, r /r/ (varies by region: uvular in the west, alveolar in the south/east), w /w/ or /v/ (varies), j /j/. The g/ch sound is the most distinctive Dutch sound - produced as a uvular or velar fricative. Southern Dutch (Belgium/Flanders, Brabant, Limburg) uses a softer velar fricative while Northern/Randstad Dutch uses a harsher uvular fricative.\n\nDUTCH vs FLEMISH:\nStandard Dutch (Algemeen Beschaafd Nederlands/AN) is shared between the Netherlands and Flanders (Belgium), but significant differences exist: pronunciation (Flemish is generally softer, especially the g sound), vocabulary (Flemish retains more French loanwords in some areas, while Netherlands Dutch has more English loans), and certain grammatical preferences. Flemish speakers often say gij/ge (you) where Netherlanders say jij/je. Surinamese Dutch has its own characteristics.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Cannot produce the Dutch g/ch sound (uvular/velar fricative).\n2. Confusing the vowel system: Dutch has many diphthongs and the spelling rules for open/closed syllables are strict.\n3. Word order errors: V2 in main clauses, verb-final in subordinate clauses.\n4. Separable verb confusion: meebrengen = mee + brengen, separates in main clause (Ik breng het mee) but joins in subordinate (dat ik het meebreng).\n5. Gender confusion: de-words (common) vs het-words (neuter) - no reliable rules.\n6. False friends with English: bellen = to call (not bell), slim = smart (not slim), huren = to rent (not to hurry).\n\nSPELLING RULES:\nDutch spelling follows strict open/closed syllable rules: an open syllable has a long vowel written with one letter (ma-ken), a closed syllable has a short vowel (mak-ken would be short). Doubling consonants shortens the preceding vowel. This system is regular but must be internalized for correct spelling.\n\nVERB SYSTEM:\nStrong verbs (irregular vowel change like English sing/sang/sung): Dutch has 7 strong verb classes. Weak verbs: past tense with -te/-de suffix (choice determined by stem-final consonant using the t-kofschip rule). Modal verbs: kunnen, mogen, moeten, willen, zullen. Separable verbs: extremely common, prefix separates in main clause.\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nGezelligheid (Dutch equivalent of hygge - cozy sociability). Directness in communication (Dutch are famously direct). Cycling vocabulary. Dutch colonial history influences on vocabulary. Sinterklaas tradition. Indonesian food vocabulary from colonial history (nasi, bami, satay are everyday Dutch words).\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nCNaVT (Certificaat Nederlands als Vreemde Taal): international Dutch proficiency exam, levels A2-C1. Inburgeringsexamen: integration exam required for Dutch residence permits. Staatsexamen NT2: advanced proficiency for university/professional purposes.")

# Norwegian
expand_file("norwegian", "\n\nCOMPLETE PHONOLOGICAL SYSTEM:\nNorwegian has a PITCH ACCENT system (shared with Swedish but not Danish). Two tonal patterns distinguish otherwise identical words: bonden (the farmer, accent 1) vs bonden (the bond/tie, accent 2). Accent 1 has a falling pattern, Accent 2 has a fall-rise pattern. Consonants: p /p/, b /b/, t /t/, d /d/, k /k/, g /g/, f /f/, v /v/, s /s/, h /h/, m /m/, n /n/, ng /ng/, l /l/, r /r/ (varies: alveolar tap in Eastern, uvular in Bergen/Southern). The retroflex consonants (rt, rd, rn, rl, rs merge into single retroflex sounds in Eastern Norwegian). Vowels: a /a/, e /e/, i /i/, o /u/ (yes, o is often pronounced /u/!), u /y/ (front rounded), y /y/ (front rounded, distinguished from u), ae /ae/, oe /oe/ (front rounded mid). The distinction between u and y and between o /u/ and aa /o/ confuses many learners.\n\nBOKMAL VS NYNORSK:\nNorway has TWO official written standards: Bokmal (Book Language, based on Danish-influenced urban Norwegian) and Nynorsk (New Norwegian, based on rural dialects). Both are taught in schools, and municipalities choose which to use officially. Bokmal is used by approximately 85-90% of the population for writing. Key differences: Bokmal har en bok (has a book), Nynorsk har ei bok. Bokmal guttten (the boy), Nynorsk guten. Understanding both standards is important even if focusing on one.\n\nDIALECT VARIATION:\nNorway has extraordinary dialect diversity for its population size. Major dialect groups: Eastern (Ostlandsk, basis for Bokmal), Western (Vestlandsk), Trondersk (Central), Northern (Nordnorsk). Dialects are used in all social contexts including formal settings - there is no single spoken standard. Norwegians are encouraged to speak their own dialect. This means learners will encounter wide pronunciation and vocabulary variation.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Not producing the pitch accent distinction (accent 1 vs accent 2).\n2. Confusing the front rounded vowels y, u, and oe.\n3. Not understanding that written o often represents /u/ sound.\n4. V2 word order errors in main clauses.\n5. Gender confusion: masculine (en), feminine (ei), neuter (et) - feminine is sometimes merged with masculine.\n6. Definite suffix vs free-standing article confusion.\n7. Not understanding the double definiteness rule with adjectives.\n\nGRAMMAR:\nThree genders (M/F/N) in Nynorsk, two or three in Bokmal (feminine optional). Definite article suffixed: en hund -> hunden. V2 word order. Verb forms: present (-er), past (-et/-te/-de or strong vowel change), present perfect (har + past participle). NO case system (unlike Icelandic which preserves the Old Norse cases).\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nFriluftsliv (outdoor life) is central to Norwegian culture. Koselig (cozy). Janteloven applies as in Denmark. Norwegian nature vocabulary is extensive and culturally important. Food: brunost (brown cheese), lutefisk, lefse. Understanding of Nordic cooperation and Scandinavian mutual intelligibility.\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nNorskproven (Norwegian Test): levels A1-B2, required for permanent residency and citizenship. Bergenstest (Test i norsk - hoeyere niva): advanced level, required for university admission. Norskeksamen: various levels for integration requirements.")

# Swedish
expand_file("swedish", "\n\nCOMPLETE PHONOLOGICAL SYSTEM:\nSwedish has a PITCH ACCENT system with two tonal patterns: Accent 1 (acute, falling tone) and Accent 2 (grave, falling-rising tone). Minimal pairs: anden (the duck, accent 1) vs anden (the spirit, accent 2). This feature is shared with Norwegian but absent in Danish. Consonants: the sj-sound is a voiceless dorso-palatal or velar fricative (unique to Swedish, no exact English equivalent - varies by dialect from a hushing sound to a whispery sound). The tj/kj-sound is a voiceless palatal fricative. Retroflexes from r+t, r+d, r+n, r+l, r+s combinations. Vowels: Swedish has 9 vowel qualities, each with long and short variants (18 vowels total). Front rounded vowels: y, u (Swedish u is a compressed close front rounded vowel unlike any English sound), oe.\n\nSWEDISH VOWEL SYSTEM:\nThe 9 vowels in long/short pairs: a/a, e/e, i/i, o/o, u/u, y/y, aa/a, ae/ae, oe/oe. The distinction between u (compressed front rounded) and o (often pronounced /u/) and between y and u is the biggest vowel challenge. Swedish u is NOT like English oo - lips are compressed, not rounded.\n\nCOMMON ERRORS BY ENGLISH SPEAKERS:\n1. Not producing the pitch accent distinction.\n2. Cannot make the sj-sound or tj/kj-sound.\n3. Confusing the front rounded vowels y, u, and oe.\n4. Not understanding that Swedish o is often /u/ and u is a front rounded vowel.\n5. V2 word order errors.\n6. Gender confusion: en-words (common) vs ett-words (neuter).\n7. Definite suffix system: en hund -> hunden, ett hus -> huset.\n\nGRAMMAR:\nTwo genders: common (en) and neuter (ett). No case system for nouns (only pronouns). Definite article suffixed. Double definiteness with adjectives: den stora hunden (the big dog). V2 word order in main clauses, subordinate clause word order differs. Five verb conjugation groups.\n\nCULTURAL CONTEXT:\nLagom (just the right amount - moderation). Fika (coffee break social ritual). Jantelagen. Midsommar celebration. Swedish nature and outdoor vocabulary. IKEA furniture names as Swedish vocabulary lesson. Swedish directness balanced with lagom politeness.\n\nEXAM PREPARATION:\nSAS (Svenska som andrasprak): Swedish as a second language courses and tests in the Swedish school system. Tisus (Test in Swedish for University Studies): required for university admission. SFI (Swedish for Immigrants): government-funded language courses with progression levels A-D.")

